            <div class="checklist-item"><div class="checklist-icon" aria-hidden="true"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none"><path d="M2 6l3 3 5-5" stroke="white" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></div><div class="checklist-text"><strong>Proof of Cohabitation (5 years)</strong><span>Joint household registration, utility bills, school enrollment records</span></div></div>
            <div class="checklist-item"><div class="checklist-icon" aria-hidden="true"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none"><path d="M2 6l3 3 5-5" stroke="white" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></div><div class="checklist-text"><strong>Sponsor Income and Asset Proof</strong><span>Bank statements showing ability to support dependent; property deeds</span></div></div>
            <div class="checklist-item"><div class="checklist-icon" aria-hidden="true"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none"><path d="M2 6l3 3 5-5" stroke="white" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></div><div class="checklist-text"><strong>No-Criminal Record Certificate</strong><span>Home country (apostilled) + local PAP clearance for applicant</span></div></div>
            <div class="checklist-item"><div class="checklist-icon" aria-hidden="true"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none"><path d="M2 6l3 3 5-5" stroke="white" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></div><div class="checklist-text"><strong>Medical Examination Report</strong><span>Designated institution results; valid within 12 months</span></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="doc-note">
            <strong>Family Reunion Note:</strong> The 5-year marriage requirement is firm; applications below that threshold are generally rejected. Foreign marriage certificates must be apostilled (or consular-legalized for non-Hague signatories) and freshly notarized within 6 months of filing.
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ===== SECTION 4: STEP-BY-STEP PROCESS ===== -->
    <section class="section section-alt" id="process" aria-labelledby="process-heading">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header center">
          <span class="section-label">How to Apply</span>
          <h2 id="process-heading" class="text-balance">The Application Process for China Permanent Residency</h2>
          <p>Once you have met your route&apos;s qualifying years, every applicant follows the same submission and review process at the Public Security Bureau (PSB).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="steps-grid" role="list" aria-label="Application steps">
          <div class="step-item" role="listitem">
            <div class="step-num" aria-hidden="true">01</div>
            <h3 class="step-title">Pre-Eligibility Check</h3>
            <p class="step-body">Confirm route eligibility: verify work permit category (A or B), continuous residency years, and income benchmarks against the 2026 city-tier thresholds for your municipality.</p>
            <span class="step-tag">Self / Specialist</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step-item" role="listitem">
            <div class="step-num" aria-hidden="true">02</div>
            <h3 class="step-title">Document Assembly</h3>
            <p class="step-body">Collect and authenticate all required documents. Arrange apostilles (or consular legalization for non-Hague signatories) from your home country and certified translations into Simplified Chinese.</p>
            <span class="step-tag">4–8 Weeks</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step-item" role="listitem">
            <div class="step-num" aria-hidden="true">03</div>
            <h3 class="step-title">Medical Exam Booking</h3>
            <p class="step-body">Book at a Chinese designated institution &mdash; only PSB-listed facilities are accepted. Schedule early; popular locations book 3&ndash;4 weeks out.</p>
            <span class="step-tag">1–3 Weeks</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step-item" role="listitem">
            <div class="step-num" aria-hidden="true">04</div>
            <h3 class="step-title">PSB Appointment</h3>
            <p class="step-body">Book an appointment with the Entry-Exit Administration Bureau at the PSB of your municipality. Online booking via the national PSB portal is available in most tier-1 and tier-2 cities.</p>
            <span class="step-tag">Book Online</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step-item" role="listitem">
            <div class="step-num" aria-hidden="true">05</div>
            <h3 class="step-title">Submit Dossier</h3>
            <p class="step-body">Attend in person with the complete dossier. Pay the government fees (CNY 1,500 application + CNY 300 card issuance = CNY 1,800 total). Receive acknowledgment receipt and estimated decision date.</p>
            <span class="step-tag">CNY 1,800 Fees</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step-item" role="listitem">
            <div class="step-num" aria-hidden="true">06</div>
            <h3 class="step-title">Await Decision</h3>
            <p class="step-body">Local PSB investigation (up to 3 months) + inspection authority review (up to 2 months) + final approval by the National Immigration Administration. Respond promptly to any supplementary requests for evidence to keep your file moving.</p>
            <span class="step-tag">3–9 Months</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="steps-cta-bar">
          <div class="steps-cta-bar-text">
            <strong>Need help navigating the process?</strong>
            Seres Immigration handles end-to-end PR applications across all four routes. Book a free consultation to confirm your eligibility and outline next steps.
          </div>
          <a href="/consultation" class="btn btn-primary">Book Free Consultation</a>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- ===== SECTION 7: FAQ ===== -->
    <section class="section section-cream" id="faq" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header center">
          <span class="section-label">Frequently Asked Questions</span>
          <h2 id="faq-heading" class="text-balance">Common Questions About China Permanent Residency in 2026</h2>
          <p>Answers to the most frequently asked questions from foreign nationals navigating the application process.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-list" role="list">

          <div class="faq-item" role="listitem">
            <button class="faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-question">How can I apply for permanent residency in China as a foreigner in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 10 10" fill="none"><path d="M5 1v8M1 5h8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg>
              </span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body">
              You apply for China permanent residency by first identifying which of the four Ministry of Public Security categories applies: Investment-Based, Employment-Based, Special Contributions, or Family Reunion (Spouse). Once your route is confirmed, you authenticate foreign documents, gather Chinese-side supporting documents, complete the mandatory health examination at a designated facility, and submit at your local Public Security Bureau Entry-Exit Administration. End-to-end processing is up to six months from submission &mdash; on top of the qualifying residence years required by your route.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" role="listitem">
            <button class="faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-question">What are the necessary documents to prepare for a China permanent residency application in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 10 10" fill="none"><path d="M5 1v8M1 5h8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg>
              </span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body">
              Required documents vary by route but universally include: a valid passport, completed PSB application form (Form CRI-001), proof of income (3–5 years), individual income tax records, no-criminal-record certificates from both your home country (apostilled) and Chinese authorities, a medical examination report from a designated institution, and proof of residence in China. For Special Contributions applicants, you will also need academic credentials, award certificates, and an endorsement from your sponsoring institution. All foreign-language documents must be accompanied by certified Simplified Chinese translations.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" role="listitem">
            <button class="faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-question">Can I expedite the process for obtaining permanent residency in China in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 10 10" fill="none"><path d="M5 1v8M1 5h8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg>
              </span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body">
              There is no official government &ldquo;fast-track&rdquo; for most PR applications. The most effective way to avoid delays is meticulous document preparation: complete apostilles, certified translations, current tax records, and a health check at a designated facility. The Special Contributions route may be reviewed on a priority basis when a strong endorsement from a national or provincial body accompanies the file.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" role="listitem">
            <button class="faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-question">What fees are associated with applying for permanent residency in China in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 10 10" fill="none"><path d="M5 1v8M1 5h8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg>
              </span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body">
              Government fees total CNY 1,800: CNY 1,500 application fee plus CNY 300 card issuance fee, paid directly to the PSB at submission. Additional costs to budget for: apostille fees (typically USD 50&ndash;200 per document, by country), certified translation (CNY 100&ndash;300 per page), the medical examination at a designated facility (approximately CNY 500&ndash;1,200), and notarization in China (CNY 200&ndash;800 per document). Total out-of-pocket without consultancy support typically runs CNY 5,000&ndash;15,000.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" role="listitem">
            <button class="faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-question">Where can I find professional assistance for securing China permanent residency in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 10 10" fill="none"><path d="M5 1v8M1 5h8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg>
              </span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body">
              Seres Immigration is an immigration consultancy &mdash; not a legal practice &mdash; focused on Western expats relocating to China. We handle eligibility review, document preparation, PSB submission, and post-arrival settlement across all four PR routes. Our advisory team is led by US-trained attorneys and cross-border specialists based in Shenzhen, Shanghai, Fuzhou, and California, with senior review by Stephen YOU, J.D. (UVA Law). <a href="/consultation" style="text-decoration:underline;">Book a free consultation</a> to start.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" role="listitem">
            <button class="faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-question">What is the difference between a China Green Card and a permanent residence card?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 10 10" fill="none"><path d="M5 1v8M1 5h8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg>
              </span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body">
              “China Green Card” is the informal name for the official Permanent Residence Card (PRC) for foreigners, formally known as the “Foreigner&apos;s Permanent Residence ID Card” (&#22916;&#21448;&#21517;: &#22806;&#22269;&#20154;&#27704;&#20037;&#23621;&#30041;&#36523;&#20221;&#35777;). The term “green card” is colloquially borrowed from the American equivalent. There is no separate document called a “green card” in the Chinese immigration system. The Permanent Residence Card is valid for 10 years and must be renewed at the PSB before expiry.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" role="listitem">
            <button class="faq-trigger" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-question">What income thresholds apply for the Employment-Based route in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg width="10" height="10" viewBox="0 0 10 10" fill="none"><path d="M5 1v8M1 5h8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg>
              </span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body">
              Salary thresholds for the Employment-Based route are not published as a single national figure &mdash; they are set by each city according to its tier and adjusted year to year. Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, and Shenzhen apply the highest thresholds; second-tier cities apply lower ones. The threshold typically tracks several multiples of local average wages, accompanied by a matching individual income tax record. The most accurate number for your situation comes from your city&apos;s PSB Exit-Entry Administration or a consultation with someone who tracks the current city-by-city figures.
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ===== SECTION 8: CTA ===== -->
    <section class="section section-navy" id="contact" aria-labelledby="contact-heading">
      <div class="container container--narrow" style="text-align:center;">
        <span class="section-label">Get Expert Help</span>
        <h2 id="contact-heading" class="text-balance">Start Your China Permanent Residency Application</h2>
        <p style="margin: 1rem 0 1.5rem;">Book a free 30-minute consultation with Seres Immigration. We&apos;ll review your eligibility across all four PR routes and outline the most realistic path for your situation.</p>
        <a href="/consultation" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg">Book Free Consultation</a>
      </div>
    </section>
`;
const faqInject = `<aside class="faq-required-wrap" aria-label="Additional FAQs"><details class="faq-required"><summary>Is 'China green card' the same as 'permanent residence permit'?</summary><p>Yes — 'China green card', 'Chinese permanent residence permit', and 'Five-Star Card' all refer to the same document, officially called the Foreign Permanent Resident ID Card. The card is valid for 10 years and renewable. The Chinese government uses 'permanent residence permit' in formal documents; 'green card' is the popular Western shorthand.</p></details><details class="faq-required"><summary>Does permanent residency in China lead to Chinese citizenship?</summary><p>No — permanent residence and citizenship are entirely separate statuses. PR lets you live and work in China indefinitely without renewing your visa. Citizenship requires giving up your original passport (China does not allow dual citizenship) and is approved at the discretion of the Ministry of Public Security. Most foreign PR holders stay on PR indefinitely rather than naturalize.</p></details><details class="faq-required"><summary>Which PR route is easiest to qualify for in 2026?</summary><p>It depends entirely on your situation. The professional/employment route is the most common for working foreigners but has high salary and tax thresholds. The spouse route requires 5 consecutive years of marriage and residence. The investor route requires substantial capital tied up for 3+ years. There is no universally 'easiest' route — the right route is the one your circumstances actually fit. Book a free consultation to find out which applies to you.</p></details></aside>`;
